posts.description: Photo by @TimLaman.  The beauty of spring skiing in the Sierra Nevada – skinning uphill in a t-shirt!  @RussLaman checks out the view as we climb the upper watershed of Big Pine Creek’s South Fork on our recent trip. #earnyourturns, #Sierras, #SierraNevada, #backcountryskiing, #California, @thephotosociety, @natgeocreative.

Photo by @TimLaman.  Costa’s Hummingbird female feeding baby in her nest, photographed yesterday in the Palm Springs Airport.  Yes, that’s right, IN the airport, which is largely open air.  I don’t usually get my wildlife photography tips from United Airlines staff, but at check-in, when I was asked about all my gear and mentioned I was a wildlife photographer, a helpful agent told me of a hummingbird nest in a cactus on the way to my gate.  Score one point for UA!  Sure enough, there it was, and it just required a 15 min wait for the female to arrive for a feeding session.  I was glad that though I have to check a lot of my gear, I always have a core set of equipment in my carry-on so that in case I arrive somewhere and my luggage is delayed I can start shooting.  The ironic thing is that for the past several days shooting birds in the wild, I’d been hoping to find an active hummingbird nest without success…. until the airport.  Mommy hummingbird looked like she was just pumping nectar into baby.  Pretty cool.  To give you a sense of the size of these tiny birds, if I put a US Quarter coin in there, I could cover the baby with it.  #PalmSprings, #Hummingbird, @thephotosociety, @natgeocreative.

Photo by @TimLaman.  So how do you get water on a backcountry ski trip?  @RussLaman demonstrates the careful fishing with ski pole and water bottle to scoop some water from this not quite frozen lake without falling in.  Finding open water is a great benefit of spring ski touring because you don’t have to melt snow to get all your water like you do on mid-winter trips. #Sierras, #SierraNevada, #backcountryskiing, #California, @thephotosociety, @natgeocreative

Photo by @TimLaman.  On our Sierra Nevada backcountry ski trip last week, @RussLaman and I camped near this small lake reflecting the peaks above at sunset.  A few days in the wilderness is good for clearing your head.  It is amazing how you can forget about the outside world while just dealing with the matters at hand like navigation, staying warm, preparing food and water, avoiding avalanches, climbing mountains, and skiing down! #refreshed, #Sierras, #SierraNevada, #backcountryskiing, #California, @thephotosociety, @natgeocreative.

Photo by @TimLaman.  How did you spend Earth Day this past weekend?  I spent it exploring the spectacular wilderness of the Sierra Nevada mountains on a backcountry ski trip with my son @RussLaman, seen here making some well earned turns high in the basin of Big Pine Creek.  The Sierras have had a phenomenal snowfall this season, so there is plenty of snow left for spring skiing if you are willing to climb for it!  #ExploreNature, #Sierras, #SierraNevada, #backcountryskiing, #skiing, #California, @thephotosociety, @natgeocreative.

This image of a Bornean orangutan climbing 30 meters up from the canopy of a rainforest in Gunung Palung National Park won the “Wildlife Photographer of the Year 2016” award.  My work aims to shine light on orangutan conservation and the need to protect their rainforest homes.

Purchase signed prints of this image for $100 from April 17th - April 22nd in honor of Earth Day. Click on the link in my profile to see all the signed prints featured in @natgeocreative’s Flash Sale.

Another day at the office for @TimLaman.  I perched on this tree branch with my feet and tripod legs on a small platform that @DrewFulton had rigged up, so I could shoot hornbills feeding at a nearby fig tree.  See the recent post of Rhinoceros Hornbills here and on @NatGeo.  My goal was the elusive and endangered Helmeted Hornbills, but during four mornings at this tree, they never showed up…. That’s the way it goes with wildlife photography some times.  @reddigitalcinema, #Hornbills, #Thailand, @thephotosociety, @natgeocreative.

Photo by @TimLaman.  A Great Hornbill takes off and flies perfectly through an opening in the tree crown on a misty afternoon in the rain forest of Southern Thailand.  @NatGeo photo assistant @DrewFulton and I spent many afternoons at spectacular forest lookouts attempting to capture Helmeted Hornbills, the endangered species that is our main focus.  We had little luck with them, but photographed several other hornbill species like this Great Hornbill found in this rich #rainforest.  Still frame from RED Epic-W camera at 75fps, which allowed me to capture the bird in the exact right position.  @reddigitalcinema, #ShotonRED, #Hornbills, #Thailand, @thephotosociety, @natgeocreative.

Photo by @TimLaman.  Field camp on assignment for @NatGeo in Southern Thailand where we have been searching for Helmeted Hornbills.  @NatGeo team member @DrewFulton and Thailand Hornbill Project team sit down to dinner. Ironically, our campsite high up the mountain in the rain forest is a former illegal logging camp, where the wood left behind forms nice benches, but is a stark reminder that these birds habitat is slowly getting degraded, even in protected areas.  Thailand Hornbill Project is working hard to try to save hornbills across the region.  I’ll share more Behind-the-Scenes shots here over the coming days so you can see what goes into doing the kind of wildlife photography I do.  #Hornbills, #Thailand, @thephotosociety, @natgeocreative

Photo by @TimLaman.  A Rhinoceros Hornbill lets out a call while foraging in a fig tree in Thailand.  I’ve been in the field these recent weeks pursuing the critically endangered Helmeted Hornbill for @NatGeo with @DrewFulton and the team from the Thailand Hornbill Project. Sometimes in wildlife photography, you don’t get what you are after, but some other nice opportunities arise.  I was hoping for Helmeted’s to come to this fig, and spent several mornings in a blind in the canopy, but this Rhinoceros Hornbill showed up instead!  Can’t complain – one of the most awesome birds of SE Asia.  Still frame from RED Epic-W camera.  #Hornbill, #Thailand, #rainforest, @thephotosociety, @natgeocreative, @reddigitalcinema,  #ShotonRED.

Photo by @TimLaman.  American White Pelicans in flight over Sunnylands.  These huge birds are magnificent at soaring and can travel long distances with little energy, riding the desert thermals between bodies of water.  Shot on a recent winter visit at Sunnylands as part of a new project I’m working on documenting the bird life of this sanctuary in Rancho Mirage, Calif.  Learn more about @Sunnylands and how you can visit at their website www.sunnylands.org.  #pelicans, #sunnylands #annenberg #birdsofsunnylands #birds #coachellavalley #palmsprings #ranchomirage

Photo by @TimLaman.  A Pied-billed Grebe pops to the surface amid a shimmering reflection of the sunlit trees beyond.  These diving birds forage for fish on the ponds at Sunnylands. Shot on a recent winter visit at Sunnylands as part of a new project I’m working on documenting the bird life of this sanctuary in Rancho Mirage, Calif.  Learn more about @Sunnylands and how you can visit at their website www.sunnylands.org.  #sunnylands #annenberg #birdsofsunnylands #birds #coachellavalley #palmsprings #ranchomirage

TL_WildlifePhotoTips:  This is an example of how paying attention to your background can make a huge difference to a photograph.  By moving myself along the shoreline of the pond, I was able to align the reflection I liked best with the position of the bird.

Photo by @TimLaman.  A Verdin feeds on flowers of an agave. TL_WildlifePhotoTips:  A shot like this doesn’t usually happen on first discovery.  Once I saw the Verdin visiting these flowers, I guessed they would be back.  Got myself into position for a nice frame, and waited….
